Introduction¶

This report analyses a number of data sets that have been obtained from Gapminder World website.

Specifically:

  • Civil liberties.
    • Index of civil liberties (EIU)
  • GDP.
    • Total GDP (PPP$, inflation adjusted)
  • Children per woman.
    • Babies per woman (total fertility rate)

The questions being asked of these data sets are:¶

  • Liberty: Has liberty increased for the planet since records began? [ 1) Use statistics to calc the global mean, 2) Bucket the scores and present visually]
  • GDP: Which countries have shown the most significant growth in GDP over the last 100 years
  • Babies per woman: With an ever increasing global population is this down to women having more babies?

Insights from the statistical analysis:¶

All statistical metrics (other than maxiumum and minimum scores) show a decrease in the liberty score across the total population.

Further analysis required...¶

Whilst the minimum score (zero) and the maximum score (one) have not changed, we do not know if there are more or less countries achieving these scores. For example: in 2006 there may have been 10 countries acheiving a maximum score of one, and in 2018 this may have reduced to just one country. The maximum score in both years is still one.

The reduction in the mean would indicate the maximum and minimum scores demonstrate a negative movement but this would need to be confirmed (see below).

Question:¶

Can further insight be obtained by presenting this visually?

Answer:¶

If we group the countries into buckets based on their scores, and then count the number of countries in each bucket for both 2006 and 2018 this may show further evidence of a movement in civil liberties

In [16]:
# Allow easy adjustment of the number of buckets in order to assess most user-friendly visual.

#Set a variable for the number of buckets which can then be changed for alternative analysis
buckets = 5

bin_edges = [-0.00001]
bin_names = []

# Populate the bin_edges and bin_names based on the number of buckets
for i in range(buckets):
    bin_edges.append((i+1)/buckets)
    bin_names.append(str((i)/buckets) + " - " + str((i+1)/buckets))
    
# Create new data columns that state which buckets the liberty score data falls into in each row    
df_lib['06bucket']= pd.cut(df_lib['2006'], bin_edges, labels=bin_names)
df_lib['18bucket']= pd.cut(df_lib['2018'], bin_edges, labels=bin_names)
In [17]:
# Set variables for the data to be presented visually.  In this instance value counts of each of the buckets.

bar_1 = df_lib['06bucket'].value_counts()[bin_names]
bar_2 = df_lib['18bucket'].value_counts()[bin_names]
In [18]:
# Plot the graph

plt.style.use('ggplot')
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
x = np.arange(buckets)
bar_width = 0.4
plt.bar(x, bar_1, width=bar_width, label='2006', color='blue' )
plt.bar(x+bar_width*0.7, bar_2, width=bar_width, label='2018', color='teal', alpha=0.8 )
plt.xlabel('Liberty score bucket (0-1)');
plt.xticks(np.arange(buckets),bin_names)
plt.ylabel('Number of countries in each bucket');
plt.title('Number of countries falling into Liberty score buckets.\n 2006 vs 2018');
plt.legend(fontsize=20);

Insight¶

The most noticeable reduction for the 2006 bucket occurs in the '0.8-1.0' bucket indicating less countries achieve the highest scores. These appear to have shifted more into the lower buckets of '0.6-0.8' and '0.2-0.4'.

Which countries have shown the most growth over the last 100 years? (1913 - 2013)¶

In order to answer this we will look at both the absolute growth in GDP and the compound annual growth rate (CAGR) over the period.

Wow - very messy but a number of insights still stand out:

- The forecasted children per women across all countries appear to be converging to approximately 2, despite significant variation in the historic actuals.
- A number of countries appear to not have any data prior to circa 1930 - up until which point the metrics are cinsistenyl flat (horizontal).  This would need to be investigated / confirmed.
- The macro trend appears to be a consistent on going reduction in the metric starting with an average of approx 6 in 1800 leading to an average of circa 2.5 in 2050.
- Numbers appeared to sink signifcantly for a number of countries around 1930/1940 (coincidentally the time of World War 2), but then increase again around 1950, and then fall again around 1980.

Clearly our selected countries (large developed nations) appear to be ahead of the broader global population, which includes a number of African, Asian and South American countries. Note though that our metrics and analysis have not been weighted for population. Each country has the same influence on the mertrics whereas in reality China and India (two of the most popularted countries) would have a much greater signifcance than smaller countries like Luxembourg.

Liberty: Has liberty increased for the planet since records began?¶

Broadly speaking liberty has not improved over the period under review from these data sets.

The mean liberty score has decreased from 0.63 in 2006 to 0.57 in 2018.

This appears to have been driven by the highest scoring countries at the start of the period achieving lower scores by the end of the period, together with other countries slipping down the scoring.

GDP: Which countries have shown the most significant growth in GDP over the last 100 years¶

Across the total population of countries included in our data set the highest growth countries were: Qatar, UAE, and Kuwait.

In our selected large developed economies, we could see that China, Australia and Japan were the largest growth countries.

Babies per woman: With an ever increasing global population is this down to women having more babies?¶

In summary: No. Across all countries it appears woman are having less children, with a noticeable decline occuring over the last 100 years.

This appears to be led by the developed nations, based on our analysis, as their fertility rates are decreasing earlier than the less developed nations however this would need to be confirmed with further analysis.
